            "title": "The personalisation paradox: How generative AI shapes conservation intentions through emotional and cognitive pathways",
            "authors": "Min Wu; Kah Mann Yong; Kum Fai Yuen",
            "keywords": "generative AI; personalisation paradox; ocean conservation; emotional resonance; cognitive engagement; conservation intentions",
            "abstract": "Ocean ecosystems face severe threats, while public engagement with conservation remains comparatively limited. This study asks whether generative AI can help bridge the awareness-action gap in ocean conservation education. It examines how three AI-enabled affordances—authenticity, knowledge acquisition, and personalisation—shape conservation intentions through emotional and cognitive pathways. Using structural equation modelling with data from 469 participants in Singapore who experienced a simulated AI conservation platform, the study tests how these affordances affect emotional resonance and cognitive engagement, and how those mechanisms subsequently influence self-efficacy and behavioural intention. The findings indicate that personalisation may be counterproductive: rather than increasing engagement, it can reduce both emotional resonance and cognitive involvement. By contrast, authentic content and comprehensive knowledge delivery are more effective in stimulating emotional and cognitive responses, which in turn promote self-efficacy and conservation intentions. The study identifies a “personalisation paradox” in AI-mediated environmental education and suggests that designers should prioritise credible, knowledge-rich, broadly resonant narratives over excessive algorithmic personalisation.",
