            "journalShort": "J. Retail. Consum. Serv.",
            "journalFull": "Journal of Retailing and Consumer Services",
            "date": "2024",
            "title": "The effects of motivated consumer innovativeness on consumer acceptance of autonomous delivery robots",
            "authors": "Min Wu; Angie Shi Qi Lin; Kum Fai Yuen",
            "keywords": "autonomous delivery robots; consumer acceptance; motivated consumer innovativeness; privacy calculus; last-mile delivery",
            "abstract": "This research aimed to examine the impacts of motivated consumer innovativeness on customers’ acceptance of autonomous delivery robots (ADRs) using the privacy calculus theory (PCT) and motivated consumer innovativeness theory (MCI). It was suggested that this impact was mediated by perceived risks and perceived cooperativeness. Four hundred and fifty survey responses were gathered through a stratified random sampling approach to effectively represent the population of Singapore, ensuring the sample’s representativeness. The acquired data underwent analysis via structural equation modelling, uncovering that motivated consumer innovativeness (MCI) (i.e. functional MCI, hedonic MCI, cognitive MCI, and social MCI) influences the perceived (privacy) risks of using ADRs. In addition, the perceived risks influence the perceived cooperativeness of ADRs. Furthermore, the perceived risks and perceived cooperativeness both influence the consumers’ acceptance of ADRs. The findings provide a nuanced understanding of consumer acceptance of ADRs, offering practical implications for logistics providers and policymakers to promote the adoption of sustainable last-mile delivery solutions.",
            "citation": "Wu, Min, Lin, Angie Shi Qi, & Yuen, Kum Fai. (2024). The effects of motivated consumer innovativeness on consumer acceptance of autonomous delivery robots. Journal of Retailing and Consumer Services, 81, Article 104030. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jretconser.2024.104030",
