            "status": "Published",
            "articleType": "Journal Article",
            "journalShort": "Comput. Hum. Behav.",
            "journalFull": "Computers in Human Behavior",
            "date": "2024",
            "title": "Effect of anthropomorphic design and hierarchical status on balancing self-serving bias: Accounting for education, ethnicity, and experience",
            "authors": "Min Wu; Zhaotong Li; Kum Fai Yuen",
            "keywords": "anthropomorphic design; hierarchical status; self-serving bias; intelligent vehicles; user accountability",
            "abstract": "This study focuses on the impact of perceived anthropomorphism and hierarchical status in intelligent vehicles on vehicle occupants' self-accountability and use intention. Anthropomorphism, which involves endowing intelligent vehicles with human-like features, is already common in non-human entities like social robots and AI devices. Hierarchical status, an important aspect of social dynamics, shapes interpersonal behaviors and perceptions. A gender-balanced sample of 72 males and 72 females was recruited online for a 2 × 2 between-subjects experiment to explore how anthropomorphic design and hierarchical status balance self-serving bias, while controlling for education, ethnicity, and experience. The findings reveal that appropriate anthropomorphic design and reasonable hierarchical status setting can effectively reduce self-serving bias, enhance users' sense of responsibility, and improve their acceptance and trust in intelligent systems, providing empirical support for the humanized design of intelligent vehicles and other AI systems.",
            "citation": "Wu, Min, Li, Zhaotong, & Yuen, Kum Fai. (2024). Effect of anthropomorphic design and hierarchical status on balancing self-serving bias: Accounting for education, ethnicity, and experience. Computers in Human Behavior, 158, Article 108299. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.chb.2024.108299",
