            "journalShort": "Marine Policy",
            "journalFull": "Marine Policy",
            "date": "2022",
            "title": "Carbon Emission Trading Scheme in the shipping sector: Drivers, challenges, and impacts",
            "authors": "Min Wu; Kevin X. Li; Yi Xiao; Kum Fai Yuen",
            "keywords": "shipping decarbonisation; carbon emission trading scheme; market-based measures; ETS; maritime policy",
            "abstract": "The shipping sector is a key contributor to global greenhouse gas emissions, and the Carbon Emission Trading Scheme (ETS) has emerged as a market-based policy instrument to drive decarbonization. This study systematically examines the drivers, challenges, and impacts of implementing ETS in the shipping sector. Based on a comprehensive review of existing policies, industry practices, and expert interviews, the study identifies the key drivers including international climate agreements, regulatory pressure, and corporate sustainability goals. It further highlights critical challenges such as carbon leakage risks, high monitoring, reporting, and verification (MRV) costs, and the uneven impact on small and medium-sized shipping enterprises. The study also analyzes the potential impacts of ETS on shipping operations, including cost structure adjustments, route optimization, and technology adoption for low-carbon fuels. The findings provide insights for policymakers and industry stakeholders to design and implement effective and equitable ETS frameworks for the shipping sector.",
            "citation": "Wu, Min, Li, Kevin X., Xiao, Yi, & Yuen, Kum Fai. (2022). Carbon Emission Trading Scheme in the shipping sector: Drivers, challenges, and impacts. Marine Policy, 138, Article 104989. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.marpol.2022.104989",
            "notes": "Volume 138, Article 104989. DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.marpol.2022.104989. CV notes: IF 3.7; CAS Sociology Q2; JCR International Relations Q1. Bibliographic metadata from uploaded CV; abstract from PAPERS.txt."
